<d4p_eqn_inline>
    <d4p_MathML><m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><m:mi>x</m:mi></m:math></d4p_MathML>
  </d4p_eqn_inline>. How many terms in the
<d4p_eqn_inline>
    <d4p_MathML><m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><m:mrow><m:mi>sin</m:mi><m:mo>⁡</m:mo><m:mi>x</m:mi></m:mrow></m:math></d4p_MathML>
  </d4p_eqn_inline> power series expansion do you need to evaluate
<d4p_eqn_inline>
    <d4p_MathML><m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><m:mrow><m:mi>sin</m:mi><m:mo>⁡</m:mo><m:mn>.5</m:mn></m:mrow></m:math></d4p_MathML>
  </d4p_eqn_inline> to 8 decimal places?</b>
</p><p>
Solution:
</p><p>
The power series expansion of 
<d4p_eqn_inline>
  <d4p_MathML><m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><m:mrow><m:mi>sin</m:mi><m:mo>⁡</m:mo><m:mi>x</m:mi></m:mrow></m:math></d4p_MathML>
</d4p_eqn_inline>
